data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem: C# 14 Span Overload Resolution

In .NET 10 / C# 14, `ReadOnlySpan<T>` and `Span<T>` overloads now participate in type inference and extension method resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (LINQ).

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` is not representable in a LINQ expression tree, so it throws at runtime.

## Fixes (pick one)

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree–compatible. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays, which now binds to the in-place `MemoryExtensions.Reverse` (returns `void`) instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
